{
  "id": "019cdf73-068d-7052-b065-2ea5ffa92ff5",
  "content": "# Design System Architecture: Personal vs corvia Brands\n\n## Decision (2026-03-12)\nPersonal marketing content (LinkedIn posts, developer journal) and corvia product content use separate brands with shared structural patterns.\n\n## Brand Separation\n- **Personal (Lim Chun Zhe)**: dark slate `#0f172a`, multi-color accents (blue, cyan, green, amber, red, purple), Inter font, discovery/journal tone\n- **corvia**: navy `#0f1b33`, gold `#D4A832`/`#E8C44E`, Poppins brand font + Inter body, professional tone\n\n## What's Shared\nTypography scale (58-68px titles down to 15px metadata), component patterns (cards, stat boxes, insight boxes, terminals), LinkedIn carousel format (1080x1350, 72px padding), and the render pipeline (Playwright + validation script).\n\n## File Locations\n- Personal design tokens: `docs/marketing/design-system.json` (brands.personal)\n- corvia brand guide: `repos/corvia/docs/brand/corvia-brand-guide.html`\n- corvia tokens also in: `docs/marketing/design-system.json` (brands.corvia) for reference\n- Skill file: `.agents/skills/visual-content-playwright.md`\n\n## Why Not a Single Design System?\nThe brands serve different audiences and purposes. Merging them would force compromises — corvia's gold accents don't fit developer journal content, and the multi-color personal palette would dilute corvia's identity. Shared structure without shared colors is the right abstraction.",
